# File Naming Convention

All files in the protocol directory should follow the pattern: `{domain}.{purpose}.{extension}`

- **domain**: The scope or area of the codebase (e.g., `chat`, `intent`, `profile`, `opportunity`)
- **purpose**: The type or role of the file (e.g., `graph`, `agent`, `generator`, `verifier`, `state`, `spec`)

## Pattern Examples

### ✅ GOOD - Following the Convention

```typescript
// Graph files
chat.graph.ts              // domain: chat, purpose: graph
chat.graph.state.ts        // domain: chat, purpose: graph.state
intent.graph.ts            // domain: intent, purpose: graph
intent.graph.spec.ts       // domain: intent, purpose: graph.spec (test)

// Agent files
router.agent.ts            // domain: router, purpose: agent
router.agent.spec.ts       // domain: router, purpose: agent.spec (test)

// Generator/processor files
response.generator.ts      // domain: response, purpose: generator
hyde.generator.ts          // domain: hyde, purpose: generator

// Other specialized files
explicit.inferrer.ts       // domain: explicit, purpose: inferrer
semantic.verifier.ts       // domain: semantic, purpose: verifier
intent.reconciler.ts       // domain: intent, purpose: reconciler
opportunity.evaluator.ts   // domain: opportunity, purpose: evaluator
```

### ❌ BAD - Not Following the Convention

```typescript
// Missing domain or purpose
chatGraph.ts              // Use: chat.graph.ts
intentAgent.ts            // Use: intent.agent.ts
generator.ts              // Use: {domain}.generator.ts
utils.ts                  // Use: {domain}.utils.ts
```

## Exceptions

The following file types are **exempt** from this convention:

- `index.ts` - Barrel export files
- `schema.ts` - Database schema files
- `main.ts` - Application entry points
- Single-purpose utility files at the root level (e.g., `constants.ts`, `types.ts`)

## Common Purpose Types

| Purpose | Description | Example |
|---------|-------------|---------|
| `.graph` | LangGraph state machines | `chat.graph.ts` |
| `.state` | State definitions | `chat.graph.state.ts` |
| `.agent` | AI agents | `router.agent.ts` |
| `.generator` | Content generators | `response.generator.ts` |
| `.evaluator` | Evaluation/scoring logic | `opportunity.evaluator.ts` |
| `.verifier` | Verification/validation | `semantic.verifier.ts` |
| `.inferrer` | Inference logic | `explicit.inferrer.ts` |
| `.reconciler` | Reconciliation logic | `intent.reconciler.ts` |
| `.controller` | API controllers | `chat.controller.ts` |
| `.service` | Business logic services | `intent.service.ts` |
| `.queue` | Job queue definitions | `intent.queue.ts` |
| `.spec` | Test files | `router.agent.spec.ts` |

## Naming New Files

When creating a new file:

1. Identify the **domain/scope**: What area does this belong to? (e.g., chat, intent, profile)
2. Identify the **purpose/type**: What does this file do? (e.g., agent, graph, generator)
3. Combine: `{domain}.{purpose}.ts`

Example: Creating a new validator for messages
- Domain: `message`
- Purpose: `validator`
- File name: `message.validator.ts`
